{"parse":{"title":"Swan-neck bottle","pageid":43647186,"revid":747747083,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:172px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:MBAM_1963.Dg.1,_swan-neck_bottle.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/MBAM_1963.Dg.1%2C_swan-neck_bottle.JPG/170px-MBAM_1963.Dg.1%2C_swan-neck_bottle.JPG\" width=\"170\" height=\"400\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/MBAM_1963.Dg.1%2C_swan-neck_bottle.JPG/255px-MBAM_1963.Dg.1%2C_swan-neck_bottle.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/MBAM_1963.Dg.1%2C_swan-neck_bottle.JPG/340px-MBAM_1963.Dg.1%2C_swan-neck_bottle.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"2268\" data-file-height=\"5340\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:MBAM_1963.Dg.1,_swan-neck_bottle.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>18th or 19th century swan-neck bottle, <a href=\"/wiki/Montreal_Museum_of_Fine_Arts\" title=\"Montreal Museum of Fine Arts\">Montreal Museum of Fine Arts</a></div></div></div>\n<p><b>Swan-neck bottles</b>, also referred to as <i><b>ashkd\u0101n</b></i> in <a href=\"/wiki/Persian_language\" title=\"Persian language\">Persian</a>, are a type of ornamental glass bottle made in <a href=\"/wiki/Iran\" title=\"Iran\">Iran</a>, characterized by their long neck. \n</p><p>These bottles are the best-known examples of an Iranian glassware tradition that began under the reign of Shah <a href=\"/wiki/Abbas_I_of_Persia\" title=\"Abbas I of Persia\">Abbas I</a> (1587\u20131629), notably in <a href=\"/wiki/Shiraz\" title=\"Shiraz\">Shiraz</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Isfahan\" title=\"Isfahan\">Isfahan</a>, and which was inspired by 16th-century <a href=\"/wiki/Venetian_glass\" title=\"Venetian glass\">Venetian glassware</a> imported into the Muslim world.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ekhtiar_280_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ekhtiar_280-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Paintings from the <a href=\"/wiki/Safavid_dynasty\" title=\"Safavid dynasty\">Safavid</a> period indicate that the bottles were used to hold wine or other beverages,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ekhtiar_280_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ekhtiar_280-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> or to adorn wall niches.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MBAM_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MBAM-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Folklore has it that they were also used as <a href=\"/wiki/Rose_water\" title=\"Rose water\">rose water</a> sprinklers and to collect the tears of wives separated from their husbands, hence the Persian appellation <i>ashkd\u0101n</i>, \"container for tears\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ekhtiar_280_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ekhtiar_280-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> There is no generally accepted explanation for the particular shape and length of these bottles' neck.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ekhtiar_280_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ekhtiar_280-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the 19th century, many swan-neck bottles were collected by European travellers and brought to Europe, where they were much in demand. They are still being produced in Iran.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MBAM_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MBAM-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Swan-neck_bottle&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table role=\"presentation\" class=\"mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox\" style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td class=\"mbox-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"40\" clas